<h2>Why Psychology and Chronic Pain?</h2>
<p>Chronic pain — pain lasting more than three months — involves complex interactions between biological, psychological, and social factors. This is not a philosophical position; it reflects the neuroscience of pain. Pain is not simply a signal from damaged tissue transmitted to the brain. It is an output of the brain, constructed from multiple inputs: sensory information, emotional state, attention, beliefs about pain, memory, and context.</p>

<p>Research consistently shows that psychological factors — catastrophising about pain, fear-avoidance, depression, anxiety, social isolation — predict pain outcomes better than most physical measures. This means psychological intervention is not an alternative to taking pain seriously; it is a direct mechanism of pain management.</p>

<h2>The Fear-Avoidance Model</h2>
<p>One of the most important psychological mechanisms in chronic pain is fear-avoidance. When pain is interpreted as a sign of serious damage or danger (catastrophising), it generates fear. Fear leads to protective avoidance of movement and activity. But avoidance maintains the pain — through deconditioning, muscle tension, reinforcement of the threatening interpretation, and loss of the activities that provide meaning and quality of life.</p>

<p>The pain-fear-avoidance cycle is self-sustaining and expands over time, progressively limiting the person's world. Therapy interrupts this cycle directly.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Psychological Approaches</h2>

<h3>CBT for Chronic Pain</h3>
<p>CBT for chronic pain has extensive evidence — multiple meta-analyses show significant reductions in pain intensity, pain interference, disability, depression, and catastrophising. It addresses:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Catastrophic beliefs about pain (identifying and testing them)</li>
  <li>Fear-avoidance behaviour (graduated exposure to avoided activities)</li>
  <li>Activity pacing — modulating activity to remain engaged without boom-bust cycles</li>
  <li>Sleep, relaxation, and stress management</li>
</ul>

<h3>ACT for Chronic Pain</h3>
<p>ACT for chronic pain shifts the goal from pain reduction to life engagement — the ability to pursue what matters regardless of pain. Its core process, psychological flexibility, involves accepting that pain may be present without fighting it or organising life around eliminating it. Multiple RCTs show ACT produces improvements in pain acceptance, functioning, and quality of life even when pain intensity itself doesn't change.</p>

<h3>Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)</h3>
<p>PRT is a newer approach based on the neuroplasticity of pain. It teaches the brain to reinterpret primary pain signals as non-dangerous, fundamentally changing the pain experience. A 2021 RCT in JAMA Psychiatry found 66% of people with back pain had no pain or near-no pain after a 4-week PRT course, compared to 10% in placebo. This is a significant finding in pain psychology.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Does this mean my pain is "all in my head"?</strong><br/>
No. Pain is real regardless of its cause. The brain constructs pain from real input — including tissue damage, nerve sensitisation, and other biological factors. Psychological approaches work through real neurological mechanisms. They don't suggest pain isn't real; they address the mechanisms that amplify and maintain it.</p>

<p><strong>Can therapy help if I have a diagnosed physical cause for my pain?</strong><br/>
Yes. Psychological factors influence pain across all types, including pain with clear structural causes. CBT and ACT help people live better despite pain even when the underlying physical cause hasn't changed.</p>

<p><strong>What's the difference between this and being told to "just think positive"?</strong><br/>
Enormously different. Positive thinking suppresses rather than processes difficult experience. CBT and ACT work with accurate perception and psychological flexibility — not avoidance of negative experience.</p>

